# Empirical Model \label{Model}

The general population model of the Probit regression is:
\begin{align}
Y = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1} X_{1} + \beta_{2} X_{2} + ... + \beta_{k} X_{k} + \mu   \label{eq1}
\end{align} Where 
\begin{align}
P(Y = 1 \mid X_{1}, X_{2}, ..., X_{k}) = \Phi(\beta_{0} + \beta_{1} X_{1} + \beta_{2} X_{2} + ... + \beta_{k} X_{k})\notag
\end{align}

$Y$ is a dichotomous variable that takes on a value of $1$ or $0$,  $X_{1}, X_{2}, ..., X_{k}$ are regressors, $\Phi(\cdotp)$ is the cumulative standard normal distribution function, and $\mu$ is the error term (Hanck, Arnold, Gerber & Schmelzer, 2020:317).

It is assumed that:
\begin{align}
E(Y \mid X) = P(Y = 1 \mid X) = \Phi(\beta_{0} + \beta_{1}) \notag \\
\Phi(z) = P(Z \le z), Z \sim \sf norm(0, 1) \notag
\end{align}

The base model (regression 1) for this paper looks at the probability that a person is employed ($P(Y = 1)$), given his/her highest level of education, age, race, gender and marital status (these factors are the regressors in \ref{eq1}).

The second regression builds on this first model by adding a variable for health status (poorhealth). The final regression extends the second regression by accounting for short term health issues with the variable shorthealth.

The final model is given by the equation:
\begin{align}
P(employment) = & \beta_{0} + \beta_{1} matric + \beta_{2} tertiary + \beta_{3} age  + \notag \\ & \beta_{4}  agesquared  + \beta_{5} raceColoured + \beta_{6} raceAsian/Indian  + \notag \\ & \beta_{7} raceWhite +  \beta_{8} male + \beta_{9} married + \beta_{10} poorhealth  +  \notag \\ & \beta_{11} shorthealth + \mu   \notag
\end{align}
Table 4.1. summarises the regression results. 


