# Results and Discussion \label{Discussion}

The base model shows that education, age, race (with the exception of the Asian/Indian group), gender and marital status are all statistically significant at 1%. The Probit regression coefficients give the change in the z-score for a one unit change in the independent variable. The signs of the coefficients indicate whether the presence of/an increase in the independent variable is associated with an increase or decrease in the probability of a person being employed. The variables ‘matric’, and ‘tertiary’ both have positive coefficients in the three regressions. This suggests a person is more likely to be employed if he/she has a matric or a tertiary qualification, compared to someone who has neither qualification, ceteris paribus.

The probability of being employed increases with age, up until some turning point, after which the probability decreases as age increases – all else being equal. This is shown by ‘age’ having a positive coefficient and ‘age_squared’ having a negative coefficient. The positive coefficients on the race categorical variables shows that being Coloured, Asian/Indian or White is associated with a higher probability of being employed, compared to a person who is African (the base group), ceteris paribus. The variable ‘male’ has a positive coefficient in all three regressions, which suggests that men are more likely to be employed than women, holding all else constant. The likelihood of being employed is positively associated with being married, ceteris paribus.

The second regression introduces the variable “poorhealth”, which is statistically significant at 5%. The negative coefficient shows that poor health is associated with a lower probability of being employed, when controlling for education, age, race, gender and marital status. This is consistent with the literature and other empirical studies (see Pelkowski & Berger, 2004; and Schuring et al. 2007). The third regression incorporates short-term health issues, ‘shorthealth’, which also has a negative coefficient. However, it is not statistically significant, which suggests that short term health problems do not substantially affect the probability of being employed.

The regression results show that education increases the Z score the most, which implies it is associated with a higher probability of employment than the other explanatory variables. Given South Africa’s history of a dichotomous labour force, an argument could be made that those who have less access to quality healthcare, likely don’t have access to quality education either and thus have a lower probability of being employed. This would be a case of the indirect causation mechanism, where the confounding variable is access to quality social services. Theoretically to account for this in a regression, a variable for ‘access to quality social services’ should be included in the model. Unfortunately, accurately quantifying such a variable is practically challenging. 

It could also be that for those who are less educated, having poor health could have a larger negative effect on the probability of being employed than those who have higher levels of education. This is because the type of work that employs more educated people, can be more flexible and accommodating of the health conditions of its workers. For example, a software engineer could work remotely from home, whereas a labourer would have to be physically present as his/her workplace. If these two employees both had poor health or lived with a chronic illness, the software engineer is more likely to remain employed due to the nature of his/her work. This could be captured in the regression with an interaction effect by including a term for the product of ‘poorhealth’ and the education variables.


<!-- hfill can be used to create a space, like here between text and table. -->

# Conclusion

Using NIDS data, this essay presented empirical evidence of the relationship between poor health and employment in South Africa. The Probit regression indicates that poor health plays a small but significant role in explaining the probability that an individual is employed. The model results show that poor health is negatively associated with the probability of being employed. However, the regression analysis suggests that, in the South African case, education is a better predictor of the likelihood of employment. This finding is consistent with the literature.

